message.content:
We need to “extract” the portion of the transactions that lead to an unpaid liability. In our case only purchase transactions that were not “Paid” and were processed using the “Account Payable” payment method affect the Accounts Payable balance.

Step 1. The “Initial” rows do not include any payable entry so we assume the beginning balance is zero.

Step 2. We scan the “Purchase” transactions that list a payment method of “Account Payable” (and – in most cases – are “Unpaid”). In our data the following purchase records qualify:

• Purchase20231231005 – Amount = 35,000.0  
• Purchase20231231009 – Amount = 50,000.0  
• Purchase20231231012 – Amount = 35,000.0  
• Purchase20231231013 – Amount = 45,000.0  
• Purchase20231231014 – Amount = 400,000.0  
• Purchase20231231018 – Amount = 90,000.0  
• Purchase20231231020 – Amount = 30,000.0  
• Purchase20231231026 – Amount = 140,000.0

Step 3. We add these amounts:
  35,000 + 50,000 = 85,000  
  85,000 + 35,000 = 120,000  
  120,000 + 45,000 = 165,000  
  165,000 + 400,000 = 565,000  
  565,000 + 90,000 = 655,000  
  655,000 + 30,000 = 685,000  
  685,000 + 140,000 = 825,000

So, the ending balance of Accounts Payable is 825,000.

Thus the answer is as follows:

```json
{"solution": {"Accounts Payable Initial Value": "0.00", "Accounts Payable End Value": "825000.00"} }
```
